metadata.name: Control the Simulation generative music #12
metadata.description:
Generative modular music track using open source music software vcv rack. A computer generated unpredictable melody plays over chords in spontaneous harmony. These chords are generated by a metallic synth sound whose notes and timbre change throughout song. A vocal phrase plays that is then randomly electronically chopped and stuttered making a statement about simulations and technology.  

With randomly generated album web art

metadata.name: Time Machine #3
metadata.description:
.:

Billions of years later we discovered a way to find our past.

:.

First, you can see how many days (and hours) have passed since the beginning of the year, with a unique color for each. Second, how many days (and hours) have passed since James Webb's first photo: July 11, 2022. 

:.

Click to switch; 
Save the image with 's'.

metadata.name: Unicorn #3334
metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. But we're the only ones who can do it. We are those magical unicorns, unique, inimitable, with our own qualities and magical abilities.
These unicorns are the visualization of our inner selves that makes our dreams come true. An embodiment of all the best with a huge positive magical power.

metadata.name: Junina #74
metadata.description:
"Junina" is a tribute to the June popular festivities in Brazil, when the streets and house facades are decorated on many cities, mainly on the Northeast Region of the country. Small flags, paper balloons, and lamps are hung on public space creating a very special atmosphere and colorful landscapes. 

Plenty of forrÃ³ (traditional music), bonfires, fireworks, typical food and drinks are part of these festivities that celebrate rural popular culture. The â€œFestas Juninasâ€ (June festivities) have an important affective place in the imaginary of the Brazilian population. 

"Junina" continues the experimentations with code of my previous work "Monotipia". The challenge of creating graphic compositions with simple elements remains. Searching and trying to delve deeper into ways to play with the rhythm and subtleties of transparencies, colors, shapes and textures.

This project is also an homage to the painters who made the Brazilian June festivities as the theme of their works, especially Alfredo Volpi (1896-1988) and Alberto da Veiga Guignard (1896-1962), but also Anita Malfatti (1889-1964), Emiliano Di Cavalcanti (1897-1976), Heitor dos Prazeres (1898-1966), and many others.

---
Features:
-> 8 palettes (rarest = grayscale)
-> 9 compositions
-> Elements: 6 geometric shapes OR mixed element compositions
-> 5 canvas formats: 
-----> tall portrait (9:16)
-----> portrait (2:3)
-----> square (1:1)
-----> landscape (3:2)
-----> wide landscape (16:9) = rarest
-> Border colors: 
-----> soft
-----> dark
-----> deep gray
-----> soberest color from palette
-----> random color from palette (rarest)

* The names of the color palettes are words related to popular June festivals. The decision to use untranslated expressions was made because these words carry many poetic meanings in Portuguese. For example, "cinza" means "gray" but also "ash". A word that refers to both the color and to the residue that results from burning wood in bonfires.

---
To save the image as a png file, type:
[1] save at actual size 
[2] save with 2000px height
[3] save with 3000px height
[4] save with 4000px height
[5] save with 5000px height

Depending on the size option, the render time can be long.

---
